@andywang219 Thank you for the advice!

I tried adding a TERMINATE event trigger as follows:
```
connect.core.initCCP(ccpDiv, {
    ccpUrl: `https://${callCenterDomain}.my.connect.aws/ccp-v2#/`,
    region: 'ap-northeast-1',
    loginPopup: true,
    softphone: {
      allowFramedSoftphone: false,
      disableRingtone: false,
    },
    storageAccess: {
      mode: "custom"
    }
  })

connect.core.initSoftphoneManager({allowFramedSoftphone: true})

const logout = () => {
  fetch(`https://${callCenterDomain}.my.connect.aws/logout`, { credentials: 'include', mode: 'no-cors'})
    .then(() => {
      connect.core.getEventBus().trigger(connect.EventType.TERMINATE);
    });
}
```

Unfortunately, even with the trigger added, I couldn't log out.

When executing the logout fetch:
- In the logout get process, all cookies are being filtered.
   The reason for filtering appears to be cross-site context?
![スクリーンショット 2023-10-24 11 54 29](https://github.com/amazon-connect/amazon-connect-streams/assets/34177860/d309255f-2de7-4972-8793-fbe15a91668f)
   
- After fetch and reloading the page, I'm not logged out from the CCP(= The CCP launches automatically without any login action).
   It seems that if I could delete the cookie from the browser, I would be able to log out. However, since the cookie has the httponly attribute, it seems I cannot delete it from within my code.

The environments I tested are:
Chrome versions: 117, 118, 119β
Experimental Flags: Storage Access API, Storage Access API permission UI, Test Third Party Cookie Phaseout all set to enabled.
![スクリーンショット 2023-10-24 12 04 47](https://github.com/amazon-connect/amazon-connect-streams/assets/34177860/328dea8a-b729-4f0f-871a-2fceaacb7fb3)

I believe there might be a need for a new method in Amazon Connect Streams to log out of the CCP.
Without this method, the workaround might be to open the logout URL in a separate window, which is visible to the user. I'd like to avoid this as it degrades the user experience.

issue.body:
Hi, is it possible to detect the start of on outgoing call and to delay starting the call, before some async function is run?

My scenario:

I want the user the select a Caller ID from a list, and when clicking on the "Call" button to put the caller id into a db, and only then to start the call. Then the caller id will be used in the Whispers Outbound flow by a Lambda function.

I tried this, but when pushing to the database the call had already started.

```
agent.onStateChange(({ newState }) => {
  if (newState === 'CallingCustomer') {
   // fetch('/push-to-db')
  }
});
```

**This is an _urgent_ issue. The agent impact here is very high as agents don't realise they've been unmuted. There is no obvious workaround at the moment and we're having to notify customers as we have no control over the CCP version embedded in the iframe**

---

It appears the CCP has pushed a release that has now impacted all application using connect streams, with an embedded CCP using `initCCP`. This has been tested in our app, a barebones app with just `initCCP` and even using the browser console/window connect with the `awsapps.com` CCP directly.

**Problem**
The CCP automatically unmutes the Agent, several seconds after a call to mute the agent using `agent.mute()`.

**Steps to Reproduce:**

- Init the CCP
- Use the connect streams method `agent.mute()`
- Observe in the console + visually in the CCP that the agent becomes unmuted after a few seconds


**Trying to find the issue:**
_Nothing in any of our app source code calls unmute, as mentioned above, this is reproducible on the AWS connect website directly._

Overriding minified files (the main.js chunk in the CCP react app), I've tracked down the following method calling unmute in the `SoftphoneContactService` file (minified):

```
 syncLocalAndRemoteMute() {
    const e = this.getContactContext()
      , t = e.currentContactState.isOnMute
      , n = e.currentContactState.isSoftphoneEnabled
      , a = this.getAgentConnection();

    a && a.isMute !== t && (n ? this.service.muteToggle(a.isMute) : this.updateContactContext({
        isOnMute: a.isMute
    }))
}
```

This consistently calls `this.service.muteToggle(false)` as the connection mute status is always `false` and the local mute status is `true`.

Interestingly in an old copy of the CCP source code this method looked like this:

```
  syncLocalAndRemoteMute() {
        if (this.isMultiparty()) {
            const context = this.getContactContext();
            const isOnMute = context.currentContactState.isOnMute;
            const isSoftphoneEnabled = context.currentContactState.isSoftphoneEnabled;
            const agentConnection = this.getAgentConnection();
            if (agentConnection && agentConnection.isMute !== isOnMute) {
                if (isSoftphoneEnabled) {
                    this.service.muteToggle(agentConnection.isMute);
                } else {
                    this.updateContactContext({
                        isOnMute: agentConnection.isMute
                    });
                }
            }
        }
    }
```

It looks like the check for multi party has been removed and this method now runs far more often, including throughout normal calls.

